LeetCode 523. Continuous Subarray Sum
Problem

Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return true if there exists a subarray of size at least 2 whose sum is a multiple of k, otherwise return false.

1. Brute Force
Idea

Check every subarray and compute sum.

If:

sum % k == 0

and subarray length ≥ 2 → return true.

Time Complexity
O(n²)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Code
class Solution {
    public boolean checkSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            int sum = 0;

            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {

                sum += nums[j];

                if (j - i + 1 >= 2 && sum % k == 0) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}

2. Prefix Sum (Better but still O(n²))
Idea

Use prefix sums to compute subarray sum in O(1).

Formula
sum(i..j) = prefix[j] - prefix[i-1]

Check:

(prefix[j] - prefix[i]) % k == 0
Time Complexity
O(n²)
Space Complexity
O(n)

Code
class Solution {
    public boolean checkSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] prefix = new int[n];

        prefix[0] = nums[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            prefix[i] = prefix[i - 1] + nums[i];
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {

                int sum = prefix[j] - (i > 0 ? prefix[i - 1] : 0);

                if (sum % k == 0) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}

3. Optimal (Prefix Sum + HashMap of Modulo)
⭐ Key Insight

We don’t need full sums.

We only care about:

(prefix[j] - prefix[i]) % k == 0

This means:

prefix[j] % k == prefix[i] % k
Idea

If two prefix sums have the same remainder, their difference is divisible by k.

Important Trick

We store:

(remainder → first index where it occurred)

We also ensure subarray length ≥ 2.

Algorithm
Create map: {0 : -1}
Maintain running sum
Compute mod = sum % k
If mod already exists:
check index distance ≥ 2 → return true
Else store mod with index
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(k) or O(n)

Code (Optimal)
class Solution {
    public boolean checkSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        map.put(0, -1);

        int sum = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            sum += nums[i];

            int mod = (k != 0) ? sum % k : sum;

            if (map.containsKey(mod)) {

                if (i - map.get(mod) > 1) {
                    return true;
                }

            } else {
                map.put(mod, i);
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}

Dry Run
nums = [23,2,4,6,7], k = 6
i	num	sum	mod (sum%6)	map	result
0	23	23	5	{0:-1,5:0}	
1	2	25	1	{1:1}	
2	4	29	5	exists at 0 → length=2 → TRUE	
Why This Works

From prefix sum identity:

(sum[j] - sum[i]) % k = 0
→ sum[j] % k == sum[i] % k

So we only track remainder repetition, not full sums.

Edge Cases
Case 1: k = 0

We directly check:

sum == 0

Handled separately in code.

Case 2: Negative numbers

Java handles % with negatives, so mod normalization may be needed in strict implementations.

Pattern Recognition
This is a:
👉 Prefix Sum + Modulo + HashMap Pattern
Core Insight
Concept	Meaning
Prefix Sum	track running sum
Modulo k	reduce problem complexity
Same remainder	divisible subarray
Final Pattern Formula
if prefix[j] % k == prefix[i] % k AND (j - i ≥ 2)
→ valid subarray exists
